nd gained fame for her erudition, her literary career foundered under the weight of slanderous charges against her sexual, professional, and religious integrity. This first biography of Copia Sulam examines the explosive relationship between gender, religion, and the press in seventeenth-century Venice through a study of the salonnière’s literary career. The backdrop to this inquiry is Venice’s tumultuous religious, cultural, and political climate and the competitive world of its presses, where men and women, Christians and Jews, alternately collaborated and clashed as they sought to gain a foothold in Europe’s most prestigious publishing capital.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aJewish women authorszItalyzVenicevBiography. 0aJewish womenzItalyzVenicevBiography. 0aSalonszItalyzVenicexHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aChristian-Jewish dialogue.  aCounter-Reformation.  aItaly.  aJewish history.  aJewish poetry.  aSara Copia Sulam.  aSarra Copia Sulam.  aVenice.  ahistory of publishing.  asalons.  awestwate.  awomen’s writing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106904530 cprintz978148750583740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753278940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487532789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487532789/original  a978-3-11-069045-3  Uni